The 150 fore-end accepts a variety of weights, which can be set up as a recoil buffer if desired.  That feature renders it superior to the later 160 model.

These guns are "designed" for 50 meter Olympic and international competition, but are IDEAL for training in "standard pistol" use due to the light trigger, and for use in indoor ranges due to the long barrel and low noise.  It can be used with any velocity ammunition, from CB or "quiet" to high power rifle ammunition.  The accuracy is so good, that they also can be used as if they were a .22lr rifle out to 100 yards and more, with appropriate ammunition.  Accuracy is about as good as the best USA made .22lr target rifles.

I never got around to shooting this rifle myself, which is why I'm selling it ("I have more guns than I have time to shoot them").   

There is some wear around the moving parts (e.g., safety lever, charging handle, bolt, magazine well, and where the receiver is fit to the top cover) that doesn't show up in the photos here.  This rifle is in good condition, but nobody is going to mistake it for a new one.


- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

"Battle Rifles"
by Larry Vickers (retired U.S. Army, Delta Force)
vickerstactical.com/tactical-tips/battle-rifles/

I frequently get asked which battle rifle is my choice for a preferred 7.62mm weapon. I have one of about every type ever made in my personal reference collection, and some are better than others in a given area, but the one I have always liked the best is the FAL. The M14 can be tuned to a higher degree of accuracy and the G3 I would consider the most rugged, but all things considered the FAL as a 7.62mm battle rifle or carbine is, in my opinion, the all around best choice.

I currently own 14 FAL style rifles of different flavors, mostly original Belgian made guns, but I would recommend a buyer look hard at DS Arms offerings if you find yourself shopping for a 7.62mm rifle or carbine vs paying the high price for a pre ban Belgian FAL. In addition DS Arms deserves the lions share of credit of keeping the FAL viable in this day and age and offering more options and varieties than Fabrique Nationale ever dreamed of. I own 3 DS Arms FAL style rifles and I find them well made, more than adequately accurate, and reliable if you know how to treat an FAL. Make no mistake the FAL is not an AK; you cannot abuse it like an AK and expect it to work. If you treat it with the respect it deserves however it will serve you quite well. Jeff Cooper said it well; “The AK is the rifle for the masses and the FAL is the rifle for the classes”. As he so often did Jeff summed up the situation perfectly; and make no mistake the FAL is the rifle for the classes.

Featuring excellent engineering the FAL has always been a weapon that holds a special place in my heart. In addition it features attention to detail and quality construction throughout. I find serious firearms enthusiasts almost always love the FAL for the sake of the remarkable design characteristics. For a serious use FAL my favorite is the tactical carbine offered by DS Arms. With an aluminum alloy lower receiver and 16.25 inch barrel it makes for a very handy 7.62mm carbine. For my particular version I used an Israeli mag release, a Norwegian AK4 style modified FAL bolt carrier with forward assist scallop, and DSA scope mount. I also mounted a Surefire flashlight with a Vltor clamp to a short piece of picatinny rail to the handguard. I topped it off with an excellent Schmidt & Bender Short Dot II scope with a 7.62 mm M118LR BDC. The S&B scope is heavy duty so to keep the weight down I opted against a DSA modular rail system. After I did a radiusing of all sharp edges DSA black Duracoated all the metal and I installed one of my VCAS slings. The end result is a superb general purpose battle carbine. It would be my first choice in a .30 caliber carbine to take into harms way.

There are countless spare parts and accessories available for the FAL on the market. Many of the parts interchange with other FAL variants so customizing your 7.62mm rifle is easier than with any other long gun save the AR family. DS Arms not surprisingly is an excellent source for FAL parts and a simple Google search will reveal several others also.

A few end user tips on the FAL: keep it reasonably clean and well lubed, learn how the gas regulator functions and how to adjust it, and only load 18 rds in the magazine. In my experience if you abide by these rules the FAL will serve you well.

I can recommend the FAL as a weapon and DS Arms as a vendor of guns, parts, and accessories for the FAL. If you are in the market for a serious 7.62mm rifle or carbine, give them a call.

title: For Sale:  .308 Sniper Rifle (Rem 700 VSSF: Varmint, Sendero, Stainless, Fluted)
postcontent:
For sale is a Remington 700 VSSF (Varmint, Sendero, Stainless, Fluted) chambered in .308 Winchester.  As the description implies, the action, barrel, and magazine follower are all Stainless Steel, making this an ideal gun to keep in the trunk for shit scenarios.  This might also become your go-to gun for hunting in the rain.  The rifle features all the extra love that Remington Smiths give to the Sendero line of rifles.  It also sports an H.S. Precision stock, commonly found on SWAT and military sniper rifles.  Adding the same stock to any other Remington 700 would cost you about $415 [ https://www.hsprecision.com/shop2/psv002.html ]

Features:
* Remington 700 VSSF:     
  $1465 MSRP per Remington (No longer available in .308 Win.)
  [ http://www.remington.com/products/firearms/centerfire/model-700/model-700-sendero-sf-ii.aspx ]

* Camoflauge Cerakote Paint Job by Predator Custom Shop
  $385

*Trigger job by Predator Custom Shop
 $75

*Badger Ordnance Oversize Bolt Knob + Gunsmithing Install
 $95

*Bushnell Banner 3-9 x 40 Scope (Camoflauged using Rustoleum)
  $75

*Harris Style Bipod (Camoflauged using Rustoleum)
 $35

*Millet Tactical 1" Rings and Bases (Cerakoted)
  $35

At retail, I've got $2,165 in this rifle.  However, it's not new.  While it shoots like a true custom made bolt action, it has suffered some light chipping of the paint and other normal wear during it's exciting life.  Rifle has been shot to 1,000 yards and holds minute of angle with 175 grain Sierra Match Kings. 

Target shown was shot with surplus M118 (Vietnam era 173 grain sniper ammo) at 100 yards off of bipod, prone.  Group Measures 0.566" outside to outside.  Subtracting out the diameter of the bullet, this group is 0.258" center to center.  That's .24 moa with 35 year old ammo.  

The golden standard for sniper-grade accuracy is 1 moa or less.  This rifle consistently shoots less than 3/4 moa with match grade ammo.  And, as you can see, will sometimes print groups as small as 1/4 moa.  The 26" barrel also allows enough velocity for the rifle to hold sub-moa all the way to 1,000 yards.

Rifle has the old style Remington trigger, tuned to break like a glass rod at 2.5 pounds.  To my knowledge, the old style triggers are no longer sold, making them increasingly desirable for custom rifle builds.  Every sniper and/or gunsmith that I've talked to highly prefers the old style triggers over the new X-Mark Pro triggers for their custom guns.  The action is also EXTREMELY smooth and easy to operate quickly for those rapid follow up shots.

Asking $1400 for everything pictured / described.  Will also throw in an unopened box of Remington Premier Match ammo (168 grain Sierra Match Kings) for the listed price.

Send me an email with your cell # in it for the quickest responses via text.  Otherwise, I'll reply to e-mails after work.

Also open to trades +/- cash for:

High quality tactical rifle scopes (Schmidt & Bender, NightForce, Leupold, US Optics, etc.) - I prefer mil/mil.
High quality .308 gas guns (LMT, GAP10, LaRue OBR, JP Enterprises, etc.)
Tactical Spotting Scopes (Leupold Mark 4, Bushnell Elite, Vortex Razor HD, etc.)
